<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-11-05T21:45:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-11-05T21:45:00-05:00" n="445" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d445">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">817.00/6069: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Nicaragua</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Eberhardt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Managua</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-11-05T21:00:00-05:45"><hi rend="italic">November 5,
                                        1928—9 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 11:54
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>American electoral information report number 10. Conservatives 49,666;
                            Liberals 67,939. Precincts reported: 362 precincts; unreported, 70.</p>
                        <p><hi rend="italic">La Prensa</hi>, chief Conservative organ, headlines
                            tonight, “The American supervision has honorably observed its promise.
                            The elections Sunday were honest, tranquil, correct, and honorable. The
                            Liberals obtained the victory.”</p>
                        <p><hi rend="italic">El Comercio</hi>, leading Liberal organ, headlines,
                            “The United States is vindicated before the world.”</p>
                        <p>Other comment similarly.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Eberhardt</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>